OctoAcme follows a structured, lifecycle-based approach to project management that prioritizes customer value, iterative delivery, and clear ownership. The methodology is organized into five core phases: Initiation, Planning, Execution, Release, and Retrospective & Continuous Improvement. During Initiation, teams validate business needs by creating a lightweight Project One-pager that defines the problem statement, success metrics, stakeholders, and initial timeline. This gate ensures alignment before significant planning effort begins. Once approved, the Planning phase breaks work into actionable, prioritized backlog items with clear acceptance criteria, estimates, and dependency mapping. This structured foundation enables the team to move into Execution with a shared understanding of goals and scope.

Execution and delivery are managed through a collaborative team rhythm and disciplined workflow discipline. Teams conduct daily 15-minute standups focused on progress and blockers, weekly delivery syncs to review milestones, and regular demos at sprint or milestone boundaries. Work flows through a project board with standardized columns (Backlog, Ready, In Progress, In Review, QA, Done), and pull requests follow strict conventions: small PRs (≤400 lines), inclusion of issue links and acceptance criteria, automated CI testing and linting, and at least one approval before merging. Quality assurance is embedded throughout execution with unit tests for new logic, integration tests where applicable, and end-to-end smoke tests for critical flows. Weekly risk register reviews and a tiered escalation process (team-level → PM → Product Lead → Sponsor) ensure blockers surface and resolve quickly.

Communication and role clarity are central to OctoAcme's success. Three primary roles anchor every project: the Project Manager coordinates delivery schedules, risks, and communications; the Product Manager defines outcomes, prioritizes the backlog, and measures success; and Developers implement features while collaborating on design and testability. Teams align through weekly syncs between PM and Product Manager, twice-weekly standups for the delivery team, and monthly stakeholder updates. Stakeholders receive consistent status using standardized templates that highlight progress, next steps, risks, and decisions needed. Once features are production-ready, they move through Release phase with pre-deployment checklists, smoke tests in staging, and post-deploy verification. Finally, Retrospectives held after each sprint or milestone capture learnings and convert them into tracked, owned action items, creating a culture of continuous improvement that feeds back into future planning cycles.
